(10, 2, 'Digicrome', 'author_images/6mMTVe29VWFXmBKkU1PJyQX6V5RVghBQNUngqMbW.webp', '100+ Data Science Fresher Interview Questions in 2024', 'As data science continues to evolve, navigating interviews in this field can be challenging and rewarding.', '<p>As data science continues to evolve, navigating interviews in this field can be challenging and rewarding. Whether you\'re a newcomer or an experienced professional, the quest for career advancement hinges on mastering various concepts, techniques, and tools.</p><p>In this guide, we\'ve meticulously curated over 100 data science interview questions tailored to the landscape of 2024. Covering a spectrum of topics ranging from foundational principles to advanced methodologies, these questions are designed to equip you with the knowledge and confidence needed to ace your next interview.<br>&nbsp;</p><p>From exploring statistical concepts to understanding <a href=\"https://www.digicrome.com/upcoming-courses/data-science-with-machine-learning\"><strong>machine learning algorithms</strong></a>, from delving into big data technologies to unravelling the intricacies of model evaluation and validation, this comprehensive compilation serves as your go-to resource for interview preparation.<br>&nbsp;</p><p>Whether you\'re penning a blog post, gearing up for interviews, or simply seeking to deepen your understanding of data science, this summary provides a succinct roadmap to help you navigate the dynamic world of data science interviews in 2024 and beyond.\"</p><h2><strong>Data Science Interview Questions for Fresher</strong></h2><h2>&nbsp;</h2><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>&nbsp;</h3><h2><strong>Foundational Concepts:</strong></h2><ol><li>What is data science, and how does it differ from traditional statistics?</li></ol><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Data science is an interdisciplinary field that utilizes scientific methods, algorithms, and systems to extract insights and knowledge from structured and unstructured data. While traditional statistics focuses on inference and hypothesis testing, data science incorporates machine learning, programming, and domain expertise to derive actionable insights from data.</p><h3>2. Define supervised and unsupervised learning with examples<br>&nbsp;</h3><p><strong>Supervised Learning:</strong></p><p>In supervised learning, the model learns from labelled data, where input data is paired with corresponding output labels. It aims to predict or classify new data based on past examples.<br>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Example: </strong>Predicting house prices based on features like square footage, bedrooms, and location.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Unsupervised Learning:</strong></p><p>In unsupervised learning, the model learns from unlabeled data, seeking to find patterns or structures within the data without explicit guidance.</p><p><strong>Example:</strong> Clustering similar documents based on their content without predefined categories.</p><h3>3. Explain the difference between classification and regression</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Classification is a type of supervised learning task where the goal is to categorize data into predefined classes or labels. Regression, on the other hand, aims to predict a continuous numerical value based on input features. For example, predicting whether an email is spam (classification) versus predicting house prices (regression).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>4. What is overfitting in machine learning, and how can it be prevented?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Overfitting occurs when a model learns to capture noise and fluctuations in the training data, resulting in poor generalization to unseen data. It can be prevented by techniques such as cross-validation, regularization, and using simpler models.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>5. Describe the bias-variance tradeoff in machine learning.</h3><p><strong>Answer: </strong>The bias-variance tradeoff refers to the balance between a model\'s ability to capture the underlying patterns in the data (bias) and its sensitivity to noise and fluctuations (variance). A high-bias model tends to underfit the data, while a high-variance model tends to overfit. Achieving an optimal tradeoff involves selecting a model complexity that minimizes both bias and variance.</p><h3>6. What are the steps involved in the data science lifecycle?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> The data science lifecycle typically involves several stages: problem definition, data collection, data cleaning and preprocessing, exploratory data analysis, feature engineering, model selection and training, model evaluation, and deployment. Additionally, the lifecycle may include iterative processes for refining models and incorporating feedback.</p><h3>7. Define feature engineering and its importance in machine learning.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Feature engineering is the process of selecting, transforming, and creating new features from raw data to improve the performance of machine learning models. It involves identifying informative features, handling missing data, scaling numerical features, encoding categorical variables, and creating new features based on domain knowledge.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>8.&nbsp;What is the significance of exploratory data analysis (EDA)?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Exploratory data analysis involves visually and statistically exploring datasets to understand their underlying patterns, distributions, relationships, and anomalies. It helps identify data quality issues, inform feature selection and engineering, uncover insights, and generate hypotheses for further analysis.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>9.&nbsp;Explain the difference between correlation and causation.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Correlation measures the strength and direction of the linear relationship between two variables, while causation indicates a direct cause-and-effect relationship between them. Correlation does not imply causation, as two variables may be correlated due to a common underlying factor or coincidence. Establishing causation requires controlled experiments or rigorous causal inference methods.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>10.&nbsp;What is the central limit theorem, and why is it important in statistics?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> The central limit theorem states that the distribution of sample means of a population approaches a normal distribution as the sample size increases, regardless of the population distribution. It is important because it allows statisticians to make inferences about population parameters based on sample statistics, even when the population distribution is unknown or non-normal.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h2><strong>Statistical Concepts:</strong></h2><h3>11. Define probability distributions and provide examples.</h3><p><strong>Answer: </strong>Probability distributions describe the likelihood of different outcomes in a random process. Examples include the normal distribution (bell curve), binomial distribution (coin flips), Poisson distribution (rare events), exponential distribution (time between events), and uniform distribution (equal probability over a range).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>12.&nbsp;What is hypothesis testing, and how is it used in data science?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Hypothesis testing is a statistical method for making inferences about population parameters based on sample data. It involves formulating null and alternative hypotheses, selecting a significance level (alpha), calculating test statistics, and making decisions about whether to reject or fail to reject the null hypothesis based on the test result.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>13.&nbsp;Explain the concept of p-value and its significance in hypothesis testing.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> The p-value is the probability of observing a test statistic as extreme as, or more extreme than, the one observed, assuming that the null hypothesis is true. It measures the strength of evidence against the null hypothesis. A smaller p-value indicates stronger evidence against the null hypothesis, leading to its rejection if below the chosen significance level.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>14.&nbsp;What are Type I and Type II errors in hypothesis testing?</h3><p><strong>Answer: </strong>Type I error occurs when the null hypothesis is incorrectly rejected when it is actually true (false positive), while Type II error occurs when the null hypothesis is incorrectly not rejected when it is actually false (false negative). The significance level (alpha) of a hypothesis test determines the probability of Type I error, while the power of the test relates to the probability of avoiding Type II error.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>15.&nbsp;Define confidence intervals and their interpretation.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> A confidence interval is a range of values calculated from sample data that is likely to contain the true population parameter with a specified level of confidence. For example, a 95% confidence interval for the population mean indicates that if the sampling process were repeated many times, 95% of the resulting intervals would contain the true population mean.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>16.&nbsp;Explain the concept of A/B testing and its applications.</h3><p><strong>Answer: </strong>A/B testing is a controlled experiment method used to compare two versions (A and B) of a webpage, product, or feature to determine which one performs better in terms of predefined metrics such as conversion rate, click-through rate, or revenue. It involves randomly assigning users to different versions, collecting data on their behaviour, and analyzing the results to make data-driven decisions.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>17.&nbsp;What is the difference between parametric and non-parametric statistics?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Parametric statistics make assumptions about the underlying distribution of the data, such as normality and homogeneity of variance, and use parameters to describe population characteristics. Non-parametric statistics, on the other hand, do not make strict assumptions about the population distribution and rely on fewer assumptions or rank-based methods.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>18.&nbsp;Define statistical power and its importance in experimental design.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Statistical power is the probability of correctly rejecting the null hypothesis when it is false (i.e., avoiding a Type II error). It is influenced by factors such as sample size, effect size, and significance level. A higher statistical power indicates a greater ability to detect true effects, making it crucial for experimental design to ensure that studies have adequate power to detect meaningful differences.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>19.&nbsp;Explain the difference between descriptive and inferential statistics.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Descriptive statistics summarizes and describes the main features of a dataset, providing insights into characteristics like central tendency and variability. Inferential statistics, on the other hand, uses sample data to make predictions or inferences about a larger population, relying on probability theory and statistical methods to conclude. Descriptive statistics focuses on analyzing observed data, while inferential statistics aims to make predictions or generalizations about populations based on sample data.</p><h3>20.&nbsp;What is sampling and its importance in statistical analysis?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Sampling involves selecting a subset of individuals or data points from a larger population to make inferences or estimates about the entire population. It is crucial in statistical analysis as it allows researchers to gather data efficiently, reduce costs, and make predictions or generalizations about populations without needing to examine every individual or data point. Sampling also helps ensure that the data collected is representative of the population, improving the reliability and validity of statistical analyses.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h2><strong>Machine Learning Algorithms:</strong></h2><h3>21. Describe decision trees and how they work.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Decision trees are hierarchical models that recursively split the data into subsets based on the most significant attribute, aiming to maximize information gain or minimize impurity at each node. They are interpretable and can be used for classification and regression tasks.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>22.&nbsp;What is logistic regression, and when is it used?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong>&nbsp;Logistic regression is a statistical method used for binary classification, where the dependent variable is categorical with two outcomes. It models the probability of the outcome using a logistic function and estimates coefficients to make predictions.</p><h3>23. Explain the working principle of support vector machines (SVM).</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Support vector machines are supervised learning models used for classification and regression tasks. They find the hyperplane that best separates classes in the feature space by maximizing the margin between the closest data points (support vectors).</p><h3>24. Define k-nearest neighbors (KNN) algorithm and its applications.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong>&nbsp;The k-nearest neighbours algorithm is a non-parametric method used for classification and regression tasks. It predicts the class or value of a new data point by averaging the values of its k nearest neighbours in the feature space.</p><h3>25. What is clustering, and provide examples of clustering algorithms.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong>&nbsp;Clustering is an unsupervised learning technique used to group similar data points based on their characteristics. Examples of clustering algorithms include K-means, hierarchical clustering, and DBSCAN.</p><h3>26. Explain the difference between K-means and hierarchical clustering.</h3><p><strong>Answer:&nbsp;</strong>K-means clustering partitions the data into a pre-specified number of clusters by minimizing the within-cluster variance, while hierarchical clustering builds a tree-like structure of clusters by recursively merging or splitting clusters based on similarity.<br>&nbsp;</p><h3>27. What is the Naive Bayes algorithm, and when is it used?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong>&nbsp;The Naive Bayes algorithm is a probabilistic classification method based on Bayes\' theorem and the assumption of independence between features. It is commonly used for text classification and spam filtering.</p><h3>28. Describe the concept of ensemble learning and its advantages.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong>&nbsp;Ensemble learning combines multiple base learners (e.g., decision trees, neural networks) to improve predictive performance, often by averaging or voting on their outputs. It can reduce overfitting, increase robustness, and capture complex patterns in the data.</p><h3>29. What is gradient descent, and how is it used in machine learning?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong>&nbsp;Gradient descent is an optimization algorithm used to minimize the cost function (error) by iteratively adjusting model parameters in the direction of the steepest descent of the gradient. It is used in training various machine learning models, such as neural networks and linear regression.</p><h3>30. Explain the working principle of neural networks.</h3><p><strong>Answer:&nbsp;</strong>Neural networks are interconnected layers of nodes (neurons) that process input data through weighted connections, apply activation functions, and generate output predictions through forward propagation. They learn complex patterns by adjusting weights during training via backpropagation.</p><h2><strong>Data Manipulation and Cleaning:</strong></h2><h3>31. How would you handle missing values in a dataset?</h3><p><strong>Answer:&nbsp;</strong>Missing values can be handled by imputation (replacing missing values with a statistical measure such as mean, median, or mode), deletion (removing rows or columns with missing values), or advanced techniques like predictive modeling.</p><h3>32. What is the importance of Data Cleansing?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Data cleansing is essential for ensuring data accuracy, consistency, and reliability. It enhances data quality, improves decision-making processes, enhances model performance, ensures compliance with regulations, and maintains data integrity and privacy.</p><h3>33. What are the important steps of Data Cleaning?</h3><p><strong>Answer:&nbsp;</strong>Different types of data require different types of cleaning, the most important steps of Data Cleaning are:</p><ol><li>Identifying data quality issues</li><li>Handling missing values</li><li>Dealing with outliers</li><li>Handling duplicate records</li><li>Standardizing data</li><li>Correcting inconsistencies</li><li>Validating data</li><li>Documenting changes</li><li>Iterative process</li><li>Ensuring data security</li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>34. What is one-hot encoding, and when is it used?</h3><p><strong>Answer: </strong>One-hot encoding is a technique used to convert categorical variables into a binary matrix representation, where each category is represented by a binary vector with one \"hot\" (1) value and the rest \"cold\" (0). It is used to handle categorical data in machine-learning models that require numerical input.</p><h3>35. Explain the process of data normalization and its importance.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Data normalization scales numerical features to a standard range (e.g., 0 to 1) to ensure that all features contribute equally to the analysis and prevent bias towards features with larger magnitudes. It is significant for distance-based algorithms like KNN and SVM.</p><h3>36. How would you handle categorical data in a dataset?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Categorical data can be handled by encoding them into numerical values using techniques like one-hot encoding or label encoding, depending on the nature of the data and the requirements of the machine learning algorithm.</p><h3>37. What is data imputation, and when is it necessary?</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Data imputation is the process of estimating missing values in a dataset using statistical techniques or machine learning algorithms. It is necessary to ensure the completeness and integrity of the data for analysis and modelling purposes.</p><h3>38. Explain the concept of data transformation.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Data transformation involves converting raw data into a more suitable format for analysis or modelling by applying mathematical operations, scaling, normalization, or encoding techniques. It aims to improve the quality, usability, and interpretability of the data.</p><h3>39. Describe the process of data cleaning and its significance.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Data cleaning involves identifying and correcting errors, inconsistencies, and anomalies in the dataset to ensure its accuracy, reliability, and relevance for analysis or modelling. It is a crucial step in the data preprocessing pipeline to obtain meaningful insights and reliable results.</p><h3>40. Describe the process of data cleaning and its significance.</h3><p><strong>Answer:</strong> Dimensionality reduction techniques aim to reduce the number of features (dimensions) in a dataset while preserving its essential information and structure. They help mitigate the curse of dimensionality, improve computational efficiency, and reduce overfitting in machine-learning models.</p>', 'blog_images/tuBM6DxRCX1jqG3f3z5r2kqkTVsCzgiRuqNODaXg.webp', 'Digicrome', 'Conquer your Data Science interview with this comprehensive guide featuring over 100 real-world questions and expert insights. Get prepared to impress and land your dream job in 2024!', 'Data Science 100+ Real-World Interview Questions (2024)', '100-data-science-interview-questions-in-2024', 91, 'published', '2025-05-30 15:32:56', '2025-07-16 15:58:25'),
(11, 2, 'Digicrome', 'author_images/iTBHfUUQUHPI7qho5uNmCoKZ8uqqpxScoC6clZzP.webp', 'Top 9 Data Science Major Trends in Upcoming Years', 'Generative AI is transforming industries because this technology opens up for tremendous output of quality content and innovative answers.', '<p><strong>1. Advances in Generative AI</strong></p>\r\n<p>Generative AI is transforming industries because this technology opens up for tremendous output of quality content and innovative answers. Models like OpenAI\'s GPT and other large language models have become valuable assets to the companies that look for creative, enrichen writing, designs, and solve problems automatically. Such technologies increase productivity and bring down the cost of production in industries.</p>\r\n<p><strong>2. Deepfake Technology</strong></p>\r\n<p>Deepfakes are growing in complexity. With high promises, there arise high big challenges. The bright side of deepfakes lies in the making and learning for innovative media. It presents many ethical dilemmas like the diffusion of lies. De-escalation of misuse should cultivate beneficial applications to handle regulation as well as proper usage of deepfakes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>3. Dominance of Python</strong></p>\r\n<p>It is one of those fields dominated by the choice of Python as a go-to programming language. So intuitive and versatile yet offering an incredibly vast array of libraries, such as Pandas, NumPy, and Scikit-learn, it forms an ideal workshop for jobs from data analysis to machine learning. It therefore simply means the strong ecosystem and interactive community keeps on making Python an important tool within <a href=\"../../upcoming-courses/post-graduate-program-in-data-science-and-artificial-intelligence\"><strong>data science course</strong></a> and professional applications.</p>\r\n<p><strong>4. Integrated AI Solutions across All Ends</strong></p>\r\n<p>Indeed, there is a great demand for all-rounded AI solutions in the market, where organizations need one stop to fulfill every aspect of that- be it data collection, processing, analysis, model deployment, and the works-all through one platform. And that alone is a trend towards updated workflows and one-stop-shop solutions that would cut through the dirtiness of having multiple tools and processes, which can drive better results earlier.</p>\r\n<p><strong>5. Data Analyst Emergence</strong></p>\r\n<p>There is no doubt about the demand for a data analyst. The recent surge in big data decision-making abilities in relation to industries is bringing in the need for recruitment, relating the data and meaningful insight to decide the business, mechanisms that can boost productivity and raise the revenue level. As this volume of data keeps growing with a sense of awareness regarding what kind of actionable insights data analysis can have utilized for, it remains an in-demand job.</p>\r\n<p><strong>6. Consumer Data Protection</strong></p>\r\n<p>Data protection concerns have brought the attention of data protection ever higher to consumers\' data protection. Businesses need to come up with new and existing data protection policies in place, including the GDPR, as well as new national rules, which bind companies to build better ways of handling data and increase transparency and so on, which makes data protection part of their operation strategies.</p>\r\n<p><strong>7. Skilling through Competitions</strong></p>\r\n<p>Online forums like Kaggle give an open and free opportunity for data scientists, both aspirant as well as seasoned practitioners, for honing their skills in competitions and solving the real-world problems.&nbsp;Experience and exposure through participation in competitions expose professionals to a wide variety of challenges, keeping them updated in industry practices, and helps build portfolios.</p>\r\n<p><strong>8. Defending Against Adversarial AI</strong></p>\r\n<p>As such machine learning models advance, the adversarial attacks in line with their vulnerabilities do as well. More so to such an extent, such a kind of AI attack, which revolves around manipulating input data with a purpose behind it-to deceive them in fact-demands innovative defense mechanisms. Whilst such models are still accurate and reliable in applications relating to safety-critical ones, security systems, and financial platforms, research is gaining momentum in designing models resilient against such attacks.</p>\r\n<p><strong>9. Regulation of AI and Policy</strong></p>\r\n<p>This pace of adoption has led the situation to where the governments of this world begin to come up with or propose, regulations on responsible use. Such regulations shall avert misuse, ensure that AI operations be fair and transparent, and introduce accountability. The establishment of such regulations shall set an atmosphere to accelerate the deployment of technology with ethical considerations safeguarded.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This is an outline that shows how fast data science is innovating, especially with emergent trends in productivity, innovation, and ethics in the digital landscape &mdash; all of which are explored in depth through our <a href=\"../../courses/data-science-training-course-in-delhi\"><strong>Data Science Course in Delhi</strong></a>.</p>', 'blog_images/w8NOJvaOFgv4p4zYFZOwWlRNwUQVKDEGZrS5mH5Q.webp', 'Data Science Course in Bangalore,\r\nData Science Training Course in Bangalore,\r\nData Science Certification Course in Bangalore,\r\nData Science Courses in Bangalore with Placement,\r\nBest Data Science Training Institute in Bangalore,\r\nData Science Course in Bangalore Fees,\r\nTop Data Science Institute in Bangalore,\r\nOnline Data Analytics Course in Bangalore,', 'Digicrome provides the latest trends and tools that cover in upcoming years. Data science is expected to see significant advancements in areas such as AI, ML, and many more.', 'Top Data Science Latest Trends and Tools for Upcoming Years | Digicrome', 'top-9-data-science-major-trends-in-upcoming-years', 65, 'published', '2025-05-30 15:57:05', '2025-07-15 22:02:29'),
(12, 2, 'Digicrome', 'author_images/BtYq4wpPAhpERgnOAK0D0br9gBa2DRurWhejfNKr.webp', 'What is Data Visualization and Its Main Tools and Techniques?', 'There are varied tools and techniques used to give data a visual format. These include tools like Tableau, Excel, and Power BI, and techniques such as charts, graphs, and many more.', '<p>Data visualization, at its simplest, can be said as the storytelling of data in a pictorial format to make it easy and simple to understand at a glance by the human brain. There are varied tools and techniques used to give data a visual format. These include tools like Tableau, Excel, and Power BI, and techniques such as charts, graphs, and many more. This is to explain data trends, patterns, and connections and help businesses make reasonable, proper, and quick decisions.</p><p><strong>What are Data Visualization Tools?</strong></p><p>Data visualization plays a great role in data comprehension; it creates meaning from what otherwise may be considered just raw numbers, which require time for analysis. Tools are a must, as they can be said to be the medium through which data visualization takes place. The tools are responsible for beautifying the insights and making them understandable at a glance.</p><p>While there are many tools available in the market, the main effective tools are:&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Tableau:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Tableau makes data analysis easy to perform and changes insights into interactive visuals. It also creates connectivity with various data sources.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Microsoft Power BI:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>This tool combines with Microsoft products and enables AI-based data visualization alongside insights and features like customizable reports and secure sharing options.</p><p><strong>Google Charts:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>This tool allows interactive visualizations with live data updates and can be incorporated into web applications using JavaScript.</p><p><strong>Excel:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Excel allows for quick data trends and pattern visualization with its diverse charts and pivoting tools. This makes data analysis easy.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>QlikSense:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>This tool is best for users to explore and picture data logically, with insights from AI custom dashboards, or graphics, without relying on IT assistance or expertise.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Python:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Python in data visualization serves a different purpose; it is used for data comprehension with libraries like Matplotlib, Seaborn, and Plotly. These enable customizable, detailed data analysis and provide the possibility for attractive, high-level, or even animated presentations.</p><p>These tools are crucial for creating impactful or visionary data that can be understood without any hassle.</p><p><strong>What are Data Visualisation Techniques?</strong></p><p>While the tools are the medium that makes meaning out of data, the techniques can be said to be the methods of data presentation. This is because they are responsible for how the analysis turns out in shape or how the presentation looks. Moreover, the data you work with will influence the method you will use, as this will change the interpretation of the content.&nbsp;</p><p>Here are some of the methods:</p><p><strong>Pie Chart:</strong> A circular graph portioned in slices each of which represents data. The key use is to show percentages or data in proportion.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Bar Chart:</strong> This chart has rectangular bars for data representation. Each bar’s length equals the proportional value it shows, easing group data comparisons.</p><p><strong>Line Chart:</strong> This is where values are represented by straight lines and are used to show trends over time. For example: sales growth, temperature, etc. it\'s used to understand anything fluctuations or eventual growth within data.</p><p><strong>Heat Map:</strong> used more for areas such as web analytics, finance, etc this technique uses color to present values and the color intensity depends on the level of value it\'s showing. Used more often for huge datasets.</p><p>Data visualization simplifies vast and difficult information, making easy to understand. By using tools like Tableau, Power BI, and Python, businesses can change raw data into clear, informational visuals. This helps quicker decision-making, promoting innovation, and improving overall functional effectiveness. The bottom line is that data visualization allows organizations to communicate trends and knowledge effectively, resulting in smarter business strategies.</p>', 'blog_images/eOI3yzpDaikRbYazHsoG5vKQPTBCPsxFGs2eWHlA.webp', 'Digicrome', 'Data visualization, at its simplest, can be said as the storytelling of data in a pictorial format to make it easy and simple to understand at a glance by a human brain.', 'What is Data Visualization and Its Main Tools and Techniques?', 'what-is-data-visualization-and-its-main-tools-and-techniques', 44, 'published', '2025-05-30 16:02:51', '2025-07-17 05:10:52'),
(13, 2, 'Digicrome', 'author_images/vFKPiG7hYuv6Gl953honfXgSayDfFjjbejocXpA3.webp', 'How is Data Science in 2025: Trends, Skills & Career', 'This year, businesses are heavily investing in AI automation, and Artificial Intelligence has become the centre of attention.', '<p>Data science is a fast-moving industry. This year, businesses are heavily investing in AI automation, and Artificial Intelligence has become the centre of attention. This industrial development has made data scientists among the most in-demand professionals.</p><p>So, if you are here looking for how data science is moving and what trends are in place that are influencing the skills and career of data science in general, and what can be done from your end to keep up in the industry, you are at the right place.</p><h2><strong>Data Science Trends in 2025?</strong></h2><h2><strong>AI &amp; ML are at the centre:</strong>&nbsp;If any technology is moving and getting updated at the fastest rate, it is AI, and this industry is no longer an option. Every industry is looking for data experts who also know how to work with AI and deploy Machine learning models that have the potential to make an impact around the world.</h2><h3><strong>Python &amp; SQL are still needed:&nbsp;</strong>Python appeared in 50% of data science job lists last year. SQL? Nearly 80%. These languages continue to create the base of data roles, particularly for analysis and engineering jobs.</h3><h3><strong>Cloud skills are a must:</strong>&nbsp;Companies with investments in automation are also shifting towards the cloud, and they are asking for Knowledge or experience in these platforms. Technicalities of AWS, AZURE, OR GCP have become a must for data or ML professionals.</h3><h3><strong>NLP &amp; Deep Learning are rising:</strong>&nbsp;Generative AI and chatbots are on the rise as they help automate work. Moreover, more job openings ask for NLP; this rise is from 5% to 19% within a one-year time frame. Proficiency in deep learning systems like TensorFlow or PyTorch is in high demand.</h3><h3><strong>Cross-functional skills win:</strong>&nbsp;The most sought-after professionals combine technical know-how with business insight. If you can turn data into strategy, you’re already ahead.</h3><h3><strong>Data visualisation and storytelling are a must:</strong>&nbsp;Companies now are more into data, which is presented in a way that is quick and easy to understand, enabling quick decisions. Tools like Tableau, Power BI, and Matplotlib are often used for this.</h3><h2><strong>Data Science Career Review:</strong></h2><h2>Career potential is extreme and continually getting better. Below is the table</h2><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Role</strong></td><td><strong>Average Salary (INR)</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>ML Engineer</strong></td><td><p><strong>Freshers:&nbsp;</strong>₹6–11 LPA</p><p><strong>Mid-level:&nbsp;</strong>₹10–16 LPA</p><p><strong>Senior:&nbsp;</strong>₹9–29 LPA</p></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data Scientist</strong></td><td><p><strong>Freshers:</strong> ₹6–10 LPA</p><p><strong>Mid-career:</strong> ₹10–28 LPA</p><p><strong>Managers:&nbsp;</strong>₹25–37.8 LPA</p></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data Engineer</strong></td><td><p><strong>Entry-level:&nbsp;</strong>₹4–6 LPA</p><p><strong>Mid-level:</strong> ₹8–15 LPA</p><p><strong>Senior:&nbsp;</strong>₹15–122.9 LPA</p></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data Analyst</strong></td><td><p><strong>Entry-level:&nbsp;</strong>₹3.9–7 LPA</p><p><strong>Mid-level:&nbsp;</strong>₹7–14 LPA</p><p><strong>Seniors:&nbsp;</strong>₹25.1+ LPA</p></td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>This is a generic salary range and may even go higher based on certain influential reasons such as experience, location, skills, and industry.</p><p><strong>What skills should You Focus On?</strong></p><p>These data science skills and projects can accelerate your career growth and can make a huge impact at work, as you will become competent with the most in-demand skills today in the market.</p><p><br>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>You needed to get skilled in:</strong></p><ol><li>Python, SQL, and a cloud platform</li><li>Practical projects in ML, NLP, and EDAT</li><li>Tools like Tableau, Power BI, and Seaborn</li><li>Ability to understand data yourself and make it understood in simple terms to others</li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>If you want to learn and explore a course in Data Science, Data Analytics, AI, Generative AI, or any other latest technology, Digicrome offers the right platform for you. You can browse a range of industry-relevant programs, including the <a href=\"https://www.digicrome.com/courses/data-science-training-course-in-noida\"><strong>Online Data Science Course in Noida</strong></a>, designed to make upskilling easier with beginner-to-advanced friendly content. Start your learning journey today with flexible, expert-led courses on Digicrome’s website.</p>', 'blog_images/PKTjPChzdVotUBMbNQNZI724WvGgHmoNb04pVcjY.webp', 'Digicrome', 'This year, businesses are heavily investing in AI automation, and Artificial Intelligence has become the centre of attention.', 'How is Data Science in 2025: Trends, Skills &amp; Career | Digicrome', 'how-is-data-science-in-2025-trends-skills-career', 87, 'published', '2025-05-30 16:09:09', '2025-07-16 18:24:38'),
(14, 2, 'Digicrome', 'author_images/0Ix7JCTP9wuGeIZ1ggZI6C6ucg2yn1HEASzzVL4z.webp', 'Difference Between Data Science and Artificial Intelligence: Exploring The Core Differences', 'Data scientists use AI to build predicting models and automate the process of data analysis.', '<p>Here are the Core Differences Between Data Science and AI</p>\r\n<p><strong>Purpose:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Data Science:</strong> Focuses on analysing and data interpreting to generate valuable insights.</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>AI:</strong> Aims to build intelligent systems that can perform tasks autonomously, often improving as they learn from data.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Scope:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Data Science:</strong> Its approach to data analysis, using statistical methods, data cleaning, and visualization techniques.</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>AI:</strong> A subset of computer science and machine learning that focuses on creating systems capable of performing intelligent tasks.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Techniques Used:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Data Science:</strong> It is analysed and data interpret with statistics, data visualization, and ML algorithms.</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>AI:</strong> It generally use ML, neural networks and deep learning with make decisions autonomously.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Outcome:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Data Science:</strong> It often a set of insights or predictions, which help businesses make informed decisions.</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>AI:</strong> It is an intelligent system or model that can automatically act tasks or solve problems in real-time.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Interdependence:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Data Science:</strong> Uses AI techniques as a tool to analyze data, particularly in the case of machine learning.</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>AI:</strong> Depends on big amounts of data (often processed by data scientists) to give trainning algorithms and models.</p>\r\n<p><strong>How They Work Together</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Data Science and AI</strong> frequently work ability-in-control to resolve real-world difficulties. Data scientists use AI to build predicting models and automate evaluation, while AI depends on data science to gain and advance over time.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>For example, to predict consumer mix up, data scientists resolve past data and implement machine learning to build models that improve with new inputs.</p>\r\n<p>If you want to gain proficient abilities in specific inquiries, Digicrome&rsquo;s <a href=\"../../upcoming-courses/data-science-training-course-in-mumbai\"><strong>Data Science Course in Mumbai</strong></a> offers experiential preparation, certain projects, and expert guidance to help you master the field.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Real-World Applications:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Data Science:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Business Intelligence:</strong> Analyzing sales data to make business decisions.</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Healthcare:</strong> Identifying patterns in patient data to improve diagnosis.</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Marketing:</strong> Analyzing customer needs to target advertisements.</p>\r\n<p><strong>AI:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Autonomous Vehicles:</strong> Self-driving cars that create decisions based on sensor data.</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Virtual Assistants:</strong> Siri or Alexa, which understand voice commands and perform tasks.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Fraud Detection:</strong> AI algorithms identifying unusual patterns in financial transactions.</p>', 'blog_images/HsxnkIrGwjZCFSjUiQ0Fo0Ne4Jfilbm96Irlgq4J.webp', 'Digicrome', 'This is core difference of Data Science and AI. Digicrome determine the difference and provide the combine Data Science and AI Course.', 'Diff. b/w Data Science and Artificial Intelligence', 'diff-b-w-data-science-and-artificial-intelligence-exploring-their-core-differences', 45, 'published', '2025-05-31 13:47:12', '2025-07-15 09:54:11'),
(15, 2, 'Digicrome', 'author_images/Vs6kMWl7B4S4PU0olhIjr3FMzT4oI7dq22shx890.webp', 'What is DeepSeek AI: China’s Power Move in the Global AI Race', 'Artificial Intelligence is developing at a fast pace, and DeepSeek AI is individual of current models making headlines.', '<p>Artificial Intelligence is developing at a fast pace, and DeepSeek AI is individual of current models making headlines. Developed in China, DeepSeek AI is a huge artificial intelligence model that aims to competing main AI systems like OpenAI’s GPT models. With developing advances in natural language processing (NLP), machine learning, and generative AI, DeepSeek AI is expected to play a critical role in creating the <a href=\"https://www.digicrome.com/upcoming-courses/Advance-Certification-program-in-artificial-intelligence-machine-learning\"><strong>Future of AI Uses</strong></a>.</p><p>Explores what DeepSeek AI is, its features, enchantment developers, and how it compares to current AI models.</p><p><strong>What is DeepSeek AI?</strong></p><p>DeepSeek AI is an advanced Chinese artificial intelligence model designed to perform tasks such as document creation, expression reading, and human-like exchange. It is advanced enough to compete with the best AI technologies from the West, including models from OpenAI, Google, and Meta.</p><p>The DeepSeek AI model is built utilizing big datasets and is skilled in handling complex queries, making it effective for tasks like the content concept, question-solving summarization, and chatbot utilizations. With China’s developing focus on AI research and self-sufficiency in technology, DeepSeek AI is a big step toward reducing dependency on Western AI systems.</p><p><strong>Key Features of DeepSeek AI</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Advanced Language Processing:</strong> DeepSeek AI is skilled to understand and create human-like reactions with extreme accuracy.</li><li><strong>Multilingual Capabilities:</strong> It supports multiple languages, making it a powerfu